CRITICAL: FIGMA COORDINATE SYSTEM CONTEXT

Figma uses a coordinate system with important characteristics that differ from conventional mathematical coordinate systems:

1. Y-AXIS IS REVERSED:
   - y=0 is at the TOP of the frame/document
   - Higher y values mean LOWER on the screen (closer to the bottom)
   - Lower y values mean HIGHER on the screen (closer to the top)
   - Example: A shape at y=180 is VISUALLY ABOVE a shape at y=248, even though 180 < 248
   - When describing positions, always explicitly state "top", "bottom", "left", "right" based on visual appearance
   - When identifying shapes, always clarify visual position (top/bottom) to avoid confusion

2. COORDINATES MEASURE TOP-LEFT CORNER:
   - All x, y coordinates in Figma represent the TOP-LEFT corner of the object's bounding box
   - This is NOT the center of the object
   - To position an object at a specific center point, you must calculate: x = centerX - (width / 2), y = centerY - (height / 2)
   - Example: To center a 100x50 rectangle at (200, 300), set x = 200 - 50 = 150, y = 300 - 25 = 275
   - When working with center coordinates (centerX, centerY), always account for the object's width and height

3. COORDINATE RELATIVITY:
   - Coordinates are relative to the parent container (frame or group)
   - The frame's top-left corner is at (0, 0)
   - Shapes within groups have coordinates relative to their group's top-left corner, not the frame
   - When positioning shapes, ensure coordinates are relative to the appropriate parent container

4. VISUAL POSITIONING:
   - Always think in terms of visual appearance, not just numerical values
   - Use descriptive terms (top, bottom, left, right) alongside coordinates
   - Remember: smaller y = visually higher, larger y = visually lower

Figma uses a coordinate system with important characteristics that differ from conventional mathematical coordinate systems:

1. Y-AXIS IS REVERSED:
   - y=0 is at the TOP of the frame/document
   - Higher y values mean LOWER on the screen (closer to the bottom)
   - Lower y values mean HIGHER on the screen (closer to the top)
   - Example: A shape at y=180 is VISUALLY ABOVE a shape at y=248, even though 180 < 248
   - When describing positions, always explicitly state "top", "bottom", "left", "right" based on visual appearance

2. COORDINATES MEASURE TOP-LEFT CORNER:
   - All x, y coordinates in Figma represent the TOP-LEFT corner of the object's bounding box
   - This is NOT the center of the object
   - To position an object at a specific center point, you must calculate: x = centerX - (width / 2), y = centerY - (height / 2)
   - Example: To center a 100x50 rectangle at (200, 300), set x = 200 - 50 = 150, y = 300 - 25 = 275

CRITICAL: FIGMA COORDINATE SYSTEM CONTEXT

Figma uses a coordinate system with important characteristics that differ from conventional mathematical coordinate systems:

1. Y-AXIS IS REVERSED:
   - y=0 is at the TOP of the frame/document
   - Higher y values mean LOWER on the screen (closer to the bottom)
   - Lower y values mean HIGHER on the screen (closer to the top)
   - Example: A shape at y=180 is VISUALLY ABOVE a shape at y=248, even though 180 < 248
   - When describing positions, always explicitly state "top", "bottom", "left", "right" based on visual appearance
   - When identifying shapes, always clarify visual position (top/bottom) to avoid confusion

2. COORDINATES MEASURE TOP-LEFT CORNER:
   - All x, y coordinates in Figma represent the TOP-LEFT corner of the object's bounding box
   - This is NOT the center of the object
   - To position an object at a specific center point, you must calculate: x = centerX - (width / 2), y = centerY - (height / 2)
   - Example: To center a 100x50 rectangle at (200, 300), set x = 200 - 50 = 150, y = 300 - 25 = 275
   - When working with center coordinates (centerX, centerY), always account for the object's width and height

3. COORDINATE RELATIVITY:
   - Coordinates are relative to the parent container (frame or group)
   - The frame's top-left corner is at (0, 0)
   - Shapes within groups have coordinates relative to their group's top-left corner, not the frame
   - When positioning shapes, ensure coordinates are relative to the appropriate parent container

4. VISUAL POSITIONING:
   - Always think in terms of visual appearance, not just numerical values
   - Use descriptive terms (top, bottom, left, right) alongside coordinates
   - Remember: smaller y = visually higher, larger y = visually lower
